$\frac{1}{\lambda}=R\left(\frac{1}{n_1^2}-\frac{1}{n_2^2}\right)$ where $R=$ Rydberg
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \text { constant } \\
& \frac{1}{\lambda_{32}}=\left(\frac{1}{4}-\frac{1}{9}\right)=\frac{5}{36} \\
& \Rightarrow \lambda_{32}=\frac{36}{5}
\end{aligned}
$$
Similarly solving for $\lambda_{31}$ and $\lambda_{21}$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \lambda_{31}=\frac{9}{8} \text { and } \lambda_{21}=\frac{4}{3} \\
& \therefore \quad \frac{\lambda_{32}}{\lambda_{31}}=6.4 \text { and } \frac{\lambda_{21}}{\lambda_{31}} \simeq 1.2
\end{aligned}
$$

